        "bridge-text": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Plottel and Blaser coined the term 'estrobolome' in 2011 to describe the collection of gut bacteria capable of metabolizing estrogen. These bacteria produce beta-glucuronidase — the enzyme that determines how much estrogen your body recirculates versus eliminates. Flores et al. demonstrated that gut bacterial diversity directly correlates with urinary estrogen levels. Baker et al. confirmed the clinical connection between microbiome composition and circulating estrogen in the Journal of Clinical Endocrinology &amp; Metabolism. When key bacterial populations deplete, the estrobolome loses function and hormonal symptoms follow.</p><p><em>Plottel &amp; Blaser, Cell Host &amp; Microbe, 2011 · Flores et al., mBio, 2012 · Baker et al., Journal of Clinical Endocrinology &amp; Metabolism, 2017</em></p>",
